; tests/socket-band.fk — L1 socket natives, sibling-witness band
;
; preludes: form-stdlib/json.fk
;
; The Form universal-translator runtime opens L1-L7 OSI mappings. L1
; needs raw byte transport beyond filesystem; TCP sockets give the wire.
; This band proves the SURFACE exists on all three kernels:
;
;   socket_listen  socket_accept  socket_connect
;   socket_send    socket_recv    socket_close
;
; Sibling-parity rule: every kernel registers every native; -1 means
; error; ≥ 0 means success. socket_close(-1) is a no-op returning -1
; on all three kernels — the one branch that is genuinely sibling-safe
; without crossing into the TS scope limit. (The TS kernel carries
; panic-stubs for the blocking natives — socket_listen/accept/connect/
; send/recv — until a worker-thread + SharedArrayBuffer shim arrives.
; Go + Rust have real implementations; see commit message for scope.)
;
; We deliberately do NOT call the panic-stub natives here. The witness
; this band carries is "socket_close exists, and the kernels agree on
; its sentinel response." That's enough proof that the native registry
; has been wired on all three kernels — the round-trip integration
; lives in scripts that drive Go and Rust as separate processes.
;
; Scoring: 1 when socket_close(-1) returns -1 on every kernel that runs
; this file, 0 otherwise. validate.sh compares stdouts; agreement is
; the conformance contract.

(do
    (let result (socket_close -1))
    (if (eq result -1) 1 0))
